To use Column-Vector-Partitioning (CVP) in SAS to manipulate a dataset, you can follow the steps below:

1. First, you need to define the library where your dataset is located using the libname statement. For example:
   ```sas
   libname mylib 'data';
   ```

2. To expand the dataset using CVP, you can use the following code:
   ```sas
   libname mylib cvp 'data';
   proc print data=mylib.class; run;
   proc contents data=mylib.class; run;
   ```

3. If you want to specify a multiplier for CVP, you can do so using the cvpmultiplier option:
   ```sas
   libname mylib cvp 'data' cvpmultiplier=1.5;
   ```

4. To save the expanded dataset as a UTF-8 data set in a different library, you can use the following code:
   ```sas
   libname outlib "output";
   proc datasets nolist;
   copy in=mylib out=outlib override=(encoding=session outrep=session) memtype=data;
   run; quit;
   proc contents data=outlib.class; run;
   ```

5. If you only want to expand a specific column (e.g., 'Name') using CVP, you can use the cvpbytes and cvpinclude options:
   ```sas
   libname mylib 'data' cvpbytes=1 cvpinclude="name";
   proc contents data=mylib.class; run;
   proc print data=mylib.class; run;
   ```

6. If you want to use CVP with SPDE, you can specify the cvpengine option as follows:
   ```sas
   libname mylib cvp 'spde' cvpengine=spde;
   proc contents data=mylib.class; run;
   ```

7. Finally, if you need to convert variables to VARCHAR using CVP, you can use the cvpvarchar option:
   ```sas
   libname mylib cvp 'data' cvpvarchar=yes;
   proc contents data=mylib.class; run;
   ```

By following these steps and using the various options available for CVP in SAS, you can effectively manipulate your dataset to suit your needs.

