```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const Accordion = ({ list }) => {
  const [openIdx, setOpenIdx] = useState(null);

  const handleClick = (idx) => {
    setOpenIdx(idx === openIdx ? null : idx);
  }

  return (
    <div>
      {list.map((item, idx) => (
        <div key={item.title}>
          <h2 onClick={() => handleClick(idx)}>
            {item.title}{openIdx === idx ? '▾' : '▸'}
          </h2>
          {openIdx === idx && <p>{item.content}</p>}
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

export default Accordion;
```

In this code, we define a functional component called `Accordion` that takes a `list` prop. The `useState` hook is used to manage the state of the currently open item's index (`openIdx`). Initially, the state is set to `null`.

The `handleClick` function is responsible for toggling the open state of an item. It takes the index of the clicked item as an argument and updates the `openIdx` state accordingly. If the clicked item is already open, the state is set to `null` to close it. Otherwise, the state is set to the clicked item's index.

Inside the `return` statement, we use the `map` method to iterate over the `list` prop and render each item as a `div` element. Each item's `title` is displayed within an `h2` element. The `onClick` event is attached to the `h2` element, which calls the `handleClick` function and passes the item's index.

To indicate the open/closed state of each item, we check if the `openIdx` state matches the current item's index. If they match, we display a downward-pointing triangle (`▾`). Otherwise, we display a right-pointing triangle (`▸`).

The content of the clicked item is conditionally rendered within a `p` element. We check if the `openIdx` state matches the current item's index, and if they match, we display the `item.content`.

By implementing this code, you will have a React application with an accordion component that displays the content of each object when clicked.

